<p><strong>Bobcat (<em>Felis rufus</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Felidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Felis rufus</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>Bobcat<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p>The Bobcat has a length of 25-30 inches, a tail length of 5 inches, and a weight of 15-35 pounds. This cat has a short tail that is black only at the tip. It has a tawny color, with indistinct dark spotting, and is white or pale below. Its ear tufts are short and inconspicuous. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.enature.com/fieldguides/detail.asp?allSpecies=y&amp;searchText=Bobcat&amp;curGroupID=5&amp;lgfromWhere=&amp;curPageNum=1" target="_blank">eNature</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This cat can be found in rimrock and chaparral areas in the West and in swamps and forests in the East. It is mostly nocturnal and solitary. It feeds on small mammals and birds, and will also eat carrion if meat is not tainted. It dens in rock crevices, hollow logs, and beneath downfalls. It bears 2-4 young at any time of the year, and has a gestation period of 50-60 days. It lives between 15-25 years in captivity.</p>
